":{"Abt 1307–1344":"about 1307–1344","1307–1344":"1307–1344","1305–1376":"1305–1376","1328–1403":"1328–1403","1330–1413":"1330–1413","–1376":"–1376","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1305":"1305","1403":"1403","1413":"1413","about 1328":"about 1328","1344":"1344","1376":"1376","1330":"1330","before 1307":"before 1307","Abt 1307":"about 1307","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Broxmouth Castle, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland","Codnor, Derbyshire, England":"Codnor, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"L'Isle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland, Durham, and Yorkshire): variant of   Lyle   and a cognate of 2 below.","French: habitational name from L'Isle or Lisle, names of several places in various parts of France, named with Old French <i>isle</i> ‘island’ (from Latin <i>insula</i>). Compare   Delisle  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lyle","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin): topographic or habitational name from Anglo-Norman French <i>del isle</i> ‘from the island’ (from Latin <i>de insula</i>), denoting someone who lived on an island or who came from a place in France named Ile, Isle, or L'Isle. The surname may also in some cases be from Lille (Nord). Compare   Lisle   and   Iles  .","Scottish: variant of   Lyall  ."]},{"name":"Lile","meanings":["English and French: variant of   Lisle  .","Scottish: variant of   Lyall  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de L'Isle was born about 1307, in Roxburghshire, Scotland as the daughter of Robert de L'Isle and Mrs Robert de L'Isle. She had at least 3 sons with John Gray Lord of Broxmouth. She died in 1344, in Codnor, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 38."},"et":{"Abt 1307–1344":"umbes 1307–1344","1307–1344":"1307–1344","1305–1376":"1305–1376","1328–1403":"1328–1403","1330–1413":"1330–1413","–1376":"–1376","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1305":"1305","1403":"1403","1413":"1413","about 1328":"umbes 1328","1344":"1344","1376":"1376","1330":"1330","before 1307":"enne 1307","Abt 1307":"umbes 1307","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","Roxburghshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Roxburghshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Broxmouth Castle, Roxbur